:::summary
*Mere Christianity* (1952) is C.S. Lewis's landmark work of Christian apologetics — an accessible, rational defense of the core beliefs shared by all orthodox Christians. Originally delivered as BBC radio broadcasts during World War II, the book presents Lewis's famous arguments from morality for the existence of God, explains the Christian understanding of Jesus Christ, and articulates what Christians believe about ethics, sin, and transformation. It is one of the most influential Christian books of the twentieth century and a perennial starting point for seekers and believers alike.
:::

